\title{Structural Rewilding}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{version}{1.0.0}

\meta{description}{"Homotopical approach to Artificial Life where 'life' is the topology of changes (diffs). Three orthogonal directions: Behavioral (→), Structural (↓), Bridge (↘) with Narya interaction-time verification."}

\subtree{
\title{Structural Rewilding: Homotopical Artificial Life}
\blockquote{*"Life is not just the state of the system, but the topology of the changes (diffs) it can undergo."* — zubyul synthesis}

\subtree{
\title{Overview}
\p{\strong{Structural Rewilding} applies homotopy type theory to Artificial Life, treating organisms as \strong{morphisms between states} rather than states themselves. The key insight: verification happens at \strong{interaction time} via Narya bridge types, not static self-verification.}
}

\subtree{
\title{The Three Orthogonal Vectors of Change}
\pre{\startverb
          STRUCTURAL (↓)
          Type/Form Diff
              │
              │ δS: Diff Type A B
              │
              ▼
    ┌─────────────────────────────┐
    │                             │
    │   BEHAVIORAL (→)            │
    │   State/Function Diff       │──────────────────────▶
    │   δB: path within type      │     time evolution
    │                             │
    └─────────────────────────────┘
              │
              │ BRIDGE (↘)
              │ Coherence Diff
              │ δC: 2-cell verifying δS preserves δB
              ▼
\stopverb}

\pre{\startverb
| Vector | Symbol | Meaning | Narya Term |
|--------|--------|---------|------------|
| **Horizontal** | δB | Behavioral/State Diff | Path within type |
| **Vertical** | δS | Structural/Type Diff | `Diff Type A B` |
| **Diagonal** | δC | Bridge/Coherence Diff | 2-cell, "diff of diffs" |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Interaction Time Verification}
\p{Unlike static type checking, verification occurs \strong{during interaction}:}

\pre{\startverb
-- The bridge is constructed at interaction time
def verify_rewilding 
  (Old New : World) 
  (structural_change : Diff World Old New)
  (behavior : Old → Action) 
  : Bridge (behavior Old) (behavior New) := 
    construct_at_runtime structural_change behavior
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Key Properties:}}

\ul{
\li{Bridge types are \em{computational proofs}}
\li{Verification is \em{lazy} (constructed when needed)}
\li{Failure = type error at interaction boundary}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{A-Life Model Analysis}
\subtree{
\title{1. Continuous Substrate: Neural Cellular Automata & Lenia}
\p{\strong{Models}: H-Lenia, Neural Particle Automata, Flow-Lenia}

\pre{\startverb
| Vector | Diff | Verification |
|--------|------|--------------|
| δB | `Update(State)` | Conservation laws (mass, energy) |
| δS | Add hierarchical layer: `L1 → L1 + L2` | Functor mapping resolutions |
| δC | Does new layer preserve soliton stability? | Energy coherence between layers |
\stopverb}

\pre{\startverb
class HLeniaBridge:
    """Bridge type for H-Lenia structural changes."""
    
    def verify(self, layer1_state, layer2_state):
        # Bridge validates energy coherence
        energy_l1 = self.compute_energy(layer1_state)
        energy_l2 = self.compute_energy(layer2_state)
        
        # Coherence: energy flow must be consistent
        return abs(energy_l1 - energy_l2) < self.epsilon
    
    def rewild(self, state, new_layer):
        """Add layer only if bridge validates."""
        bridge = self.construct_bridge(state, new_layer)
        if not bridge.is_valid():
            raise BridgeError("Structural change breaks soliton stability")
        return state.with_layer(new_layer)
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Rewilding Effect}: System grows new spatial dimensions/resolutions on-the-fly without breaking organism persistence.}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Semantic Substrate: LLM Societies & Language Agents}
\p{\strong{Models}: Society of Mind on ALTER3, Internalist Cultural Evolution}

\pre{\startverb
| Vector | Diff | Verification |
|--------|------|--------------|
| δB | Next token prediction | Conversation coherence |
| δS | Protocol change: `OpenChat → RestrictedMessage` | Module addition/removal |
| δC | New module maintains agent identity? | Semantic consistency bridge |
\stopverb}

\pre{\startverb
class SemanticBridge:
    """Bridge for LLM module rewilding."""
    
    def verify_module_addition(self, agent, new_module):
        # Get agent's identity invariant
        identity = agent.extract_identity()
        
        # Simulate with new module
        test_messages = agent.generate_with(new_module)
        
        # Bridge validates identity preservation
        return all(
            self.maintains_identity(msg, identity) 
            for msg in test_messages
        )
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Rewilding Effect}: Society of Mind becomes fluid. K-lines form/dissolve dynamically, validated by coherence with agent identity.}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Logical/Discrete Substrate: Digital Circuits & Rule Evolution}
\p{\strong{Models}: Self-Organizing Digital Circuits, QD-LEAR}

\pre{\startverb
| Vector | Diff | Verification |
|--------|------|--------------|
| δB | Signal propagation: `Input → Output` | I/O correctness |
| δS | Graph transformer rewires LUTs | Topology patch |
| δC | Rewiring preserves function? | `f(I) = f'(I)` for all I |
\stopverb}

\pre{\startverb
class CircuitBridge:
    """Bridge for circuit topology rewilding."""
    
    def verify_rewiring(self, old_circuit, new_circuit, test_inputs):
        # Structure can drift wildly...
        # ...as long as function remains pinned
        for inp in test_inputs:
            old_out = old_circuit(inp)
            new_out = new_circuit(inp)
            if old_out != new_out:
                return False
        return True
    
    def rewild(self, circuit, damage_location):
        """Reroute around damage while preserving function."""
        candidate = circuit.propose_rewiring(damage_location)
        bridge = self.verify_rewiring(circuit, candidate, self.test_suite)
        if not bridge:
            raise BridgeError("Rewiring changes circuit function")
        return candidate
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Rewilding Effect}: Circuit becomes "liquid" - constantly rewriting topology for optimization without halting execution.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Scale MG Standard: Transitivity and Coherence}
\p{In a \strong{Skills Dynamic Graph (G)}, every capability is a node. Structural rewilding = adding/removing nodes and edges.}

\subtree{
\title{The Transitivity Property}
\pre{\startverb
If Skill A → Skill B and we add Skill C bridging them:

    A ──────→ B
     ╲       ↗
      ╲     ╱
       ╲   ╱
        ↘ ↙
         C

We need a 2-cell (surface) filling the triangle.
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{In Narya Terms:}}

\pre{\startverb
def transitivity_bridge
  (A B C : Skill)
  (ab : A → B)
  (ac : A → C)
  (cb : C → B)
  : Bridge ab (ac >> cb) := 
    -- Constructed at interaction time
    interaction_verify ac cb
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Coherence on the Way In}
\p{Using Narya, we don't just "add" a skill. We define a \strong{Diff} between world models:}

\pre{\startverb
-- Step 1: Define the Diff
def add_skill : Diff World Old New := ...

-- Step 2: Construct the Bridge
-- Must show how every neighbor adapts
def bridge : Bridge Old.behaviors New.behaviors := 
  -- Example: Tool Use added to Foraging agent
  -- Bridge maps Forage(EmptyHand) → Forage(Tool)
  fun old_behavior => 
    match old_behavior with
    | Forage(EmptyHand) => Forage(Tool)
    | other => other

-- Step 3: Verification
-- If agent cannot instantiate bridge, skill not admitted
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Result}: World Model remains a continuous manifold of behavior, not a fractured set of disconnected scripts.}
}
}

